						<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">John Lions</span></h1>
						<div id="bodyContent">
								<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-navigation">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Johnlions.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Johnlions.jpg/220px-Johnlions.jpg" width="220" height="286" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/16/Johnlions.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/16/Johnlions.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Johnlions.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.23wmf17/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
John Lions with his students in 1980</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>John Lions</b> (19 January 1937 – 5 December 1998) was an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australian</a> <a href="Computer_science.html" title="Computer science">computer scientist</a>. He is best known as the author of <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lions%27_Commentary_on_UNIX_6th_Edition,_with_Source_Code" title="Lions' Commentary on UNIX 6th Edition, with Source Code">Lions' Commentary on UNIX 6th Edition, with Source Code</a></i>, commonly known as the <i>Lions Book</i>.</p>
<p></p>
